<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-09-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-09-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="547" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/2921</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LIB1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-09-04">
                                        <hi rend="italic">September 4, 1916</hi>
                                    </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 5.30 p.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4823. Your 3736, August 25. Foreign Office states that in view of
                                assurances given respecting genuine purchase of cocoa by American
                                firm, a telegram has been sent to British Consul, Guayaquil,
                                instructing him that the shipment in question should be facilitated
                                and adds that the charterers of the ship have also been notified no
                                objection now exists to acceptance for shipment of this cargo.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LIB1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>